* NPM is a package manager and the largest software registry for JavaScript.
* It consists of three components: website, command line interface (CLI), and registry.
* It is used to install, share, manage, and update project dependencies.
* It allows running packages without installing them globally using npx.
* It helps manage multiple versions and private packages within organizations.

package.json

* package.json is the manifest file of a Node.js project containing metadata.
* It includes project name, version, description, author, license, and dependencies.
* It defines scripts, entry points, and repository links.
* It acts as a configuration file for npm.

Bundler

* A bundler combines multiple JavaScript files and dependencies into a single file for browsers.
* It prepares production-ready code.
* Examples include Browserify, ESBuild, Parcel, Rollup, and Webpack.
* Create React App internally uses Webpack.

Types of Dependencies

* Dev dependencies are required only during development.
* Normal dependencies are required for production runtime.

Caret (^) and Tilde (~) in package.json

* Tilde (~) updates only patch versions while locking major and minor versions.
* Caret (^) updates minor and patch versions automatically.
* Caret is the default behavior used by npm.

package-lock.json

* It stores the exact versions of installed dependencies.
* Ensures consistency across different systems and environments.
* Prevents compatibility issues during installations.
* Important for collaborative projects.

Transitive Dependencies

* Dependencies that have their own dependencies are called transitive dependencies.
* Each dependency inside node_modules has its own package.json file.

Parcel Bundler

* Parcel is a web application bundler focused on developer experience.
* Running npx parcel index.html starts a development server.
* It watches files and automatically reloads the browser on changes.
* Running npx parcel build index.html creates an optimized production build.
* Production build includes minification and asset optimization.

NPM  (Functions)

* Installing packages locally or globally.
* Managing dependencies through package.json.
* Running scripts using npm run command.
* Publishing packages to npm registry.

NPX 

* NPX is a package runner that comes with npm.
* It allows executing packages without installing them globally.
* It can run locally installed binaries directly.
* It can download and execute packages temporarily.
* Helps avoid global installations for one-time usage.

Difference Between NPM and NPX

* NPM is used to install packages.
* NPX is used to execute packages.
* NPX avoids global installations.
* NPX is useful for temporary commands.

Why CDN Should Not Be Used for React in Projects

* Requires internet connection to load React.
* Version upgrades require manual link changes.
* Using npm installs React locally and avoids dependency issues.
* Local installation improves reliability.

Browser Scripts Cannot Have Imports/Exports

* Browser treats normal script tags as non-module scripts.
* Import statements cause errors unless script type is module.
* Adding type="module" allows import/export usage.

HMR (Hot Module Replacement)

* HMR updates modules without full page reload.
* It preserves application state during development.
* It improves development speed by updating only changed files.
* Process involves runtime checking, downloading updates, and applying them.


Parcel Performance and Cache

* Parcel creates a .parcel-cache folder for caching builds.
* Subsequent builds are faster due to caching.

Other Features of Parcel

* File compression
* Bundling
* Image optimization
* Minification
* Consistent hashing
* Differential bundling
* Diagnostics support

Removing main from package.json

* main property specifies entry point for npm.
* Parcel already receives entry point via command.
* Conflict occurs if both are present.
* Therefore main should be removed when using Parcel.

Parcel Execution Output

* Development and production builds are stored in dist folder.
* dist and .parcel-cache should not be pushed to Git.
* These folders can be regenerated anytime.

Browser Compatibility Using browserslist

* browserslist specifies supported browsers in package.json.
* Parcel uses it to generate compatible builds.
* Helps support older or specific browser versions.


